            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.27a.37-40_0001"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">37</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        Kansas City 9, Mo.
                        June 2, 1959
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neighardt<sic>Neihardt</sic>, Litt.<hi rend="caps">D.,LL.D.</hi></addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Columbia, Mo.</addrLine>
                    </address>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Doctor Neighardt<sic>Neihardt</sic>:</salute></opener> <p>I shall introduce myself by saying that I have often heard <del>D</del><add>t</add>he late Dr. Burris <hi rend="caps">A.</hi> Jenkins, quote your poetry and remark that you were the , in his opinion, the best poet, of the day, in America.</p>
                
                <p>I have known you were, or thought you were were, on the staff at <hi rend="caps">M.U.</hi> But not until I saw your biographic sketch in International Who's Who in Poetry, did I get up to nerve to write to you. Please, to acquaint yourself with <del>I</del><add>m</add>e see in <hi rend="caps">I.W.W.P.</hi> But I omitted to say I was a member of the Golden Bridle Poetry class organized by the late John Milton Smither, and hold his certificate indicating that I have written all of the required patterns, and he taught 27 rhythms. Consequently I can make any poetry pattern I choose- wh<del>ci</del><add>ic</add>h you may think they are too many now. However, I am enclosing m<del>t</del><add>y</add> trilinea rose poetry form and would appreciate it if you could have your students write the form. It has been written by many poets in more than half of the United States. I am think<del>9</del><add>i</add>ng(?) of publ<del>l</del><add>i</add>shing a small brocure<sic>brochure</sic> of about 36<add>,</add> 3 stanza sequences<add>,</add>collection of other poets' work.I know ,  a lot of roses??? Do you agree?</p>
                
                <p>Professionaly, I cared for the late Mrs. Andrew Drumm <del>9</del><add>(</add> '36,<del>3</del><add>'</add>37, '38 ) she lived next door to the late Mrs. <hi rend="caps">H.J.</hi> Waters, whose son publishes, is <add>Has <unclear>reprinted</unclear> my poems from the <hi rend="caps">K.C</hi> Stay</add> it the Columbian<del>,</del><add>?</add> there. But Dr. Joseph <hi rend="caps">C.</hi> Cleveland, was Doctor Jenkins assistant, address him, Second Congregaional Church, Rockford, Ill. He knows my husband and me.</p>
                
                <p>Excuse errors in typing. <add>+ <unclear/></add> And thank you very much for your time and interest.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Sincerely,</salute>
                    
                    <signed>Nellie Amos</signed>
                    <signed>(Mrs.<unclear/> Amos)</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
           
                
            <div1 type="enclosure">     
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.27a.37-40_0002"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">38</fw>
                
                <opener><hi rend="caps">THE TRILINEA ROSE POETRY PATTERN</hi></opener>
                
                <p>The <hi rend="underline">trilinea</hi> poetry form was created by Nellie Amos, who also coined the word - <hi rend="underline">trilinea</hi>.  The form is strictly iambic 2-4-2, or dimeter, tetrameter, dimeter.It may be written in single stanza or sequence of 3-6-9 stanzas. The 6 and 9 stanza are a rep<del>i</del><add>E</add>tion of the 3 stanza form adhering to its rhyme scheme. Example as follows.</p>
                
                <p><add>Pure
                ideal
                iambic
                only.</add></p>
                
                <add><hi rend="caps">SHOWER OF ROSES</hi></add>
                
                <del/>
                                                                            <note type="authorial">Rhyme</note>
                <lg>
                    <l>The roses bloom -                                    <hi rend="caps">A</hi></l>
                    <l>A summer shower overnight                            <hi rend="caps">B</hi></l>
                    <l>From depths of gloom.                                <hi rend="caps">A</hi></l>
                
                    <l>The crimson rose -                                   <hi rend="caps">C</hi></l>
                    <l>The lovers' passion symbol, sweet                    <hi rend="caps">Y</hi></l>
                    <l>As love's disclose.                                  <hi rend="caps">C</hi></l>
                
                    <l>And purest white -                                   <hi rend="caps">B</hi></l>
                    <l>Like innocence, perfumed, fresh -                    <hi rend="caps">Y</hi></l>
                    <l>As child delight.                                    <hi rend="caps">B</hi></l>
                </lg>
                - Nellie Amos
                
                <p>In Wednesday Magazine
                1936</p>
                
                <milestone unit="section"/><ab>***</ab>
                
                <p>The single stanza:</p>
                
                <hi rend="caps">OLD-FASHIONED ROSE</hi>
                <lg>
                    <l>The Ozarks grew -                                   <hi rend="caps">A</hi></l>
                    <l>The creamy, clustered, fragrant rose -              <hi rend="caps">Y</hi></l>
                    <l>My Mother knew.                                     <hi rend="caps">A</hi></l>
                </lg>
                
                - Nellie Amos
                
                <p>From
                Over the Ozarks, 1956. <milestone unit="section"/>
                <add>Springfield News, (<hi rend="caps">MO.</hi>)</add></p> <ab>***</ab>
                
                <p>The form is unique in that it must <hi rend="underline">always</hi> relate to the rose, or roses. No contractions. No internal rhymes. <hi rend="caps">Y</hi> means no rhyme. The form is dedicated to the Holy Trinity; hence the three equation.</p>
                
                <milestone unit="section"/><ab>***</ab>
                
                <add>
                <hi rend="caps">JIMINY CRICKET ROSES</hi>
                <lg>
                    <l>Of good repute</l>
                    <l>They sparkle blush because their name</l>
                    <l>Is simply cute.</l>
                </lg>
                
                - Nellie Amos
                </add>
                
                <p><add>In The Kansas City Star.</add></p>
                
                <p>Phillipians 4:8</p>
                
